{"id": "complexlit_PMC8024496_v4_mineral_medium_0_2_um_la_ce_rare_earth_el", "name": "V4 mineral medium (+0.2 uM La/Ce rare earth elements) (PMC8024496)", "category": "laboratory", "organism_scope": "prokaryote-generic", "aerobic": true, "description": "V4 mineral medium (+0.2 uM La/Ce rare earth elements) — medium reported in PMC8024496 (complex/undefined base — extracts not BiGG-mappable).", "namespace": "bigg", "provenance": {"source_type": "literature", "citation": "Medium composition from PMC8024496 (see GrowthDB record).", "doi": "", "url": "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8024496/", "notes": "Full recipe recovered from the primary literature: base medium 'V4 mineral medium (modified, with La/Ce rare earth elements)' (Base V4 medium: Dunfield PF et al. (2007) Methane oxidation by an extremely acidophilic bacterium of the phylum Verrucomicrobia. Nature 450:879-882, doi:10.1038/nature06411, PMID:18004300 (cited as ref 21 in PMC8024496). Rare-earth (La/Ce) addition: Pol A et al. (2014) Rare earth metals are essential for methanotrophic life in volcanic mudpots. Environ Microbiol 16:255-2", "verification": "paper-verified (recipe recovered from primary literature)", "verification_note": "Source paper PMC8024496 (Frontiers Microbiol 2021, Methylacidiphilum sp. RTK17.1) defines the medium ONLY by reference to Dunfield et al. 2007 Nature 450:879-882; the full V4 mineral base (phosphate/ammonium/Mg/Ca salts, N source, trace metals, vitamins) is NOT printed in this paper and I could not access the Dunfield 2007 recipe, so the mineral base cannot be verified and must NOT be fabricated. ", "recipe_evidence": "PMC8024496 Methods: batch cultivation on V4 medium with 0.2 uM La and Ce; methane supplied at ~10% v/v in the headspace with ~5% v/v CO2 as the C1 substrate for the standard methanotrophic growth condition. This is the same V4 base and rare-earth supplementation as the formate and methanol media; only the carbon source (CH4 gas) differs.", "recipe_confi